Some people like to solve this problem with &#x27;goto&#x27;s, as in the &#x27;small&#x27; subfunction in <a href="https://golang.org/src/pkg/math/gamma.go" rel="nofollow">https://golang.org/src/pkg/math/gamma.go</a><p>Personally I&#x27;d like to see something like Haskell&#x27;s &quot;where&quot;, to create a scope for private functions in the &quot;B style&quot;:<p><pre><code>    void largerFunction(void) {
        small1();
        small2();
    } where {
        void small1(void) {
            ...
        }
        void small2(void) {
            ...
        }
    }
</code></pre>
Until that becomes possible, we can always just make sufficiently small modules with few public functions.

Huh. That&#x27;s a little silly given the venerable HSTORE already has this capability:<p><pre><code>      create table foo (d hstore);
      insert into foo (d) values(hstore(ARRAY[&#x27;key&#x27;, &#x27;key2&#x27;], 
      ARRAY[&#x27;value&#x27;, &#x27;value2&#x27;]));
    --  &quot;key&quot;=>&quot;value&quot;, &quot;key2&quot;=>&quot;value2&quot;
      update foo set d = d || hstore(&#x27;key&#x27;, UPPER(d->&#x27;key&#x27;));
    -- &quot;key&quot;=>&quot;VALUE&quot;, &quot;key2&quot;=>&quot;value2&quot;
</code></pre>
Seems like JSON / JSONB need operators to merge two objects. In fact isn&#x27;t JSONB sharing the data format with the new HSTORE2?
